SIMPLE: mistress
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mistress
<hw>Mis"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>maistress</ets>, OF. <ets>maistresse</ets>, F.
<ets>ma⟦icir⟧tresse</ets>, LL. <ets>magistrissa</ets>, for L.
<ets>magistra</ets>, fem. of <ets>magister</ets>. See <er>Master</er>,
<er>Mister</er>, and cf. <er>Miss</er> a young woman.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A woman having power, authority, or ownership; a woman who
exercises authority, is chief, etc.; the female head of a family, a
school, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The late queen's gentlewoman! a knight's daughter!⟦br⟧
To be her <qex>mistress</qex>' <qex>mistress</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A woman well skilled in anything, or having the
mastery over it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A letter desires all young wives to make themselves
<qex>mistresses</qex> of Wingate's Arithmetic.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A woman regarded with love and devotion; she who has
command over one's heart; a beloved object; a sweetheart.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark> <rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A woman filling the place, but without the rights,
of a wife; a woman having an ongoing usually exclusive sexual
relationship with a man, who may provide her with financial support in
return; a concubine; a loose woman with whom one consorts habitually;
<as>as, both his wife and his <ex>mistress</ex> attended his
funeral</as>.</def> <rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A title of courtesy formerly prefixed to the name of
a woman, married or unmarried, but now superseded by the contracted
forms, <abbr>Mrs.</abbr>, for a married, and <abbr>Miss</abbr>, for an
unmarried, woman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>Mistress</qex> Gilpin (careful soul).</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A married woman; a wife.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several of the neighboring <qex>mistresses</qex> had assembled to
witness the event of this memorable evening.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The old name of the jack at bowls.</def>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be one's own mistress</b></col>, <cd>to be exempt from
control by another person.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mistress
<hw>Mis"tress</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To wait upon a mistress; to be
courting.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Donne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistressship</ent>⟦br⟧
